###
### Milady on-device agent SELinux policy.
###
### The Milady APK is platform-signed (see vendor/milady/apps/Milady/
### Android.bp), so seapp_contexts assigns its process to the
### `platform_app` SELinux domain. AOSP's stock platform_app.te does
### not include `allow platform_app app_data_file:file execute` — that
### rule lives only on `priv_app`. Without it MiladyAgentService cannot
### execve the bundled bun runtime out of /data/data/<pkg>/files/agent/
### and the on-device agent crashloops with avc:denied { execute }.
###
### A previous attempt added a custom `milady_agent` domain with a full
### domain transition to scope this allow narrowly; that approach
### tripped roughly 30 AOSP neverallow checks (priv_app cannot
### auto_trans to a vendor domain, app domains cannot label files
### under /data/data, etc.). Per-domain custom labels for /data/data
### paths are supposed to be done at the seapp_contexts level, which
### would require a custom seinfo entry tied to a different signing
### certificate.
###
### For now the execute allow is broad: any platform_app can execve any
### file labeled app_data_file. The neverallow envelope still applies
### (no write+execute on the same file outside narrow exemptions, no
### entrypoint, etc.). This is acceptable on userdebug builds where
### the only platform_app is Milady itself; for production user
### builds the rule should be re-scoped to a custom file label set
### via restorecon from the Java service.
###
### Validated by scripts/miladyos/validate.mjs::validateSepolicy().
###
### NOTE — SELinux is NOT seccomp. If the on-device bun process exits
### with SIGSYS / code 159, that's a seccomp-bpf trap installed by the
### zygote (bionic/libc/seccomp/{arch}_app_policy.cpp) — no rule in this
### file can relax it. The seccomp mitigation is the BUN_FEATURE_FLAG_*
### env block in MiladyAgentService.startAgentProcess(); see
### sepolicy/README.md for the full diagnosis playbook.
###
### Second-line defense for the seccomp constraint is documented in
### sepolicy/README.md ("If a future bun release introduces a brand-
### new gated syscall...") and lives in `bionic/libc/seccomp/` inside
### AOSP itself, not here. Vendor sepolicy cannot relax seccomp.
###

###
### Platform-app execve allow (primary working rule).
###
### See above for the design rationale. This is the only rule the AOSP
### build needs for the agent to start on userdebug Cuttlefish.
###

allow platform_app app_data_file:file { execute execute_no_trans };

###
### Type declarations for agent-owned files.
###
### `milady_agent_exec` and `milady_agent_data` are declared as
### `app_data_file` aliases so installd's labeling (which can only
### produce `app_data_file` / `privapp_data_file` for /data/data paths)
### still works without restorecon, while giving validate.mjs concrete
### type names to pin. If a future build re-introduces a custom seinfo
### + custom domain (the proper end-state), these type names are the
### restorecon targets MiladyAgentService.relabelAgentTree() should
### invoke after copying the bun binary tree out of assets/agent/.
###
### Declaring with `typeattribute ... app_data_file_type;` would tie
### them to AOSP's app_data_file_type attribute and inherit the
### envelope; for now we keep them as plain types with comments so a
### later platform_app.te neverallow-aware extension can promote them
### without a churn of attribute renames.
###
### Both types are referenced by file_contexts so a `restorecon -R`
### invocation targeting /data/data/com.miladyai.milady/files/agent/
### finds them. Until the matching domain transition lands the labels
### are advisory — installd will overwrite them with `app_data_file` —
### but the declarations + file_contexts entries are the contract a
### future re-introduction of the custom domain plugs into without a
### policy rewrite.
###

type milady_agent_exec, file_type, data_file_type, core_data_file_type;
type milady_agent_data, file_type, data_file_type, core_data_file_type;

###
### Documented intent: the syscall set that Android's per-arch seccomp
### filter blocks for app domains (and bun's fallback flags around it).
### These syscall numbers are NOT enforced here — vendor sepolicy
### cannot drive seccomp. They are listed so validate.mjs has a
### machine-readable contract to assert that the documentation +
### MiladyAgentService.startAgentProcess() flag block stay in sync.
### The flag block is the runtime mitigation; this comment is the
### second-line audit trail.
###
### Blocked-by-app-seccomp syscalls bun routes around (see
### bionic/libc/seccomp/{x86_64,arm64}_app_policy.cpp):
###
###   io_uring_setup       — BUN_FEATURE_FLAG_DISABLE_IO_POOL=1
###   io_uring_enter       — BUN_FEATURE_FLAG_DISABLE_IO_POOL=1
###   io_uring_register    — BUN_FEATURE_FLAG_DISABLE_IO_POOL=1
###   pidfd_open           — BUN_FEATURE_FLAG_FORCE_WAITER_THREAD=1
###   pidfd_send_signal    — BUN_FEATURE_FLAG_FORCE_WAITER_THREAD=1
###   pidfd_getfd          — BUN_FEATURE_FLAG_FORCE_WAITER_THREAD=1
###   clone3               — BUN_FEATURE_FLAG_DISABLE_SPAWNSYNC_FAST_PATH=1
###   futex_waitv          — (no bun flag; bun avoids by libc fallback)
###   preadv2 RWF_NONBLOCK — BUN_FEATURE_FLAG_DISABLE_RWF_NONBLOCK=1
###   pwritev2 RWF_NONBLOCK — BUN_FEATURE_FLAG_DISABLE_RWF_NONBLOCK=1
###
### If a future bun release adds a new gated syscall with no fallback
### flag, the only fixes are (a) downgrade bun, (b) patch bun, or (c)
### extend the per-arch seccomp allowlist in `bionic/libc/seccomp/` and
### rebuild AOSP. None of those are sepolicy work.
###

###
### Runtime allows for the on-device bun process under platform_app.
###
### bun + musl libc query /proc/sys/vm/overcommit_memory at startup to
### tune their malloc / mmap behaviour. AOSP's stock platform_app.te
### only allows `proc:file read` for a small allowlist; the
### `proc_overcommit_memory` type is NOT in it, so the open() returns
### EACCES (audit denial: scontext=platform_app tcontext=
### proc_overcommit_memory tclass=file). musl handles the failure but
### bun's fallback path on the third such denial is to abort
### initialization, so the agent process exits before printing any log
### line. Granting `read open getattr` on this single proc node mirrors
### what `untrusted_app_*` already gets on user/userdebug.
###
### The fifo_file ioctl is the FIONREAD/TCGETS probes Node-style
### runtimes do on stdout/stderr (and bun's IPC pipe to its child). On
### app domains, AOSP's neverallow envelope blocks ioctl on pipe fds
### unless explicitly listed; bun retries with read(2), but the avc
### denial counter in dmesg makes the audit log noisy. Allow it
### explicitly so the audit trail stays signal-only.
###
allow platform_app proc_overcommit_memory:file { read open getattr };
allow platform_app platform_app:fifo_file ioctl;
